<SessionPage
  title="Session 5 · C# API models: records and classes"
  heading="Model fixed request data and guarded domain state"
  lede="Today’s win: choose a record for a fixed API-shaped value and a class for an object whose state may change only through one explicit rule."
  backHref="/topics/csharp/"
  backLabel="C# sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="One design question, not a receiver drill">
    <Callout>
      Start from behaviour: is this value fixed once supplied, or does it have a lifecycle with permitted state changes? That decision shapes the public API.
    </Callout>
    <p>
      In a small backend system, a request usually describes data supplied at one moment. A domain object may instead hold state that changes under a rule. Both can have properties; the important difference is what callers are allowed to change.
    </p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Worked example: a fixed value and a guarded balance">
    <Code code={exampleCode} lang="csharp" />
    <ul>
      <li><code>Currency</code> is a positional <code>record</code>: a compact fixed description with init-only public values in this model.</li>
      <li><code>GiftCard</code> is a <code>class</code>: it has a balance that changes only through <code>Spend</code>.</li>
      <li><code>RemainingBalance</code> is public to read but has <code>private set;</code>, so a caller cannot bypass the rule by assigning a new balance.</li>
    </ul>
    <Callout>Do not turn this into “records are immutable” or “classes are mutable.” Either kind of type can be designed differently. Here the choice expresses this particular API and lifecycle.</Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="A useful TypeScript comparison">
    <p>
      TypeScript is usually <strong>structural</strong>: independently declared objects with the same required properties can often be used in the same place. C# is <strong>nominal</strong>: two separately named types remain different even if their public properties have matching names and types.
    </p>
    <p>
      That makes a named C# public surface a deliberate contract. A <code>WarehouseAddress</code> with the same three strings is not automatically a <code>ShippingAddress</code>.
    </p>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Clarification: <code>record</code> and <code>sealed</code>">
    <p>
      <code>record</code> says that a type is primarily a <strong>value-shaped model</strong>. For a record class, C# supplies useful value-oriented behaviour: a concise positional declaration, value-based equality, deconstruction, and <code>with</code>-copy syntax. It does <strong>not</strong> mean “immutable”. A record can expose mutable members, and a class can be designed to be immutable.
    </p>
    <Code code={`public record ShippingAddress(string Street, string City, string PostalCode);

var home = new ShippingAddress("River Road 1", "Gdańsk", "80-001");
var movedHome = home with { City = "Warsaw" };

// home and movedHome are separate values; this is a copy, not a mutation.`} lang="csharp" />
    <p>
      <code>sealed</code> is unrelated to mutability. It closes an inheritance branch: no type may derive from a <code>sealed class</code> or <code>sealed record</code>. In the worked example, <code>public sealed record Currency(...)</code> means “a value-shaped record which no one may extend.” The <code>sealed</code> is optional for the address exercise; use it only when you deliberately do not want derived address types.
    </p>
    <Code code={`public sealed record Currency(string Code, int DecimalPlaces);

// This would not compile:
// public class SpecialCurrency : Currency { ... }`} lang="csharp" />
    <Callout>
      Separate the questions: <strong>record or class?</strong> asks what the type represents and which generated value behaviour helps. <strong>sealed or extensible?</strong> asks whether other types may inherit from it. <strong>mutable or guarded?</strong> asks which state changes callers may make.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Your design boundary">
    <p>Stay inside one request model and one domain model. No endpoints, JSON, inheritance, interfaces, generics, validation libraries, or record internals are needed.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>ShippingAddress</code> has <code>Street</code>, <code>City</code>, and <code>PostalCode</code>. Once created, callers must not change its public values.</li>
      <li><code>Parcel</code> has a tracking number and a current status. It starts as <code>Created</code>.</li>
      <li>Callers may read the status but not set it directly.</li>
      <li>The only transition today is <code>Created</code> → <code>Dispatched</code>. A later attempt reports failure and leaves the status unchanged.</li>
    </ul>
  </SessionSection>

  <ReplyTask id="learn:csharp/005:q1" copyText={replyText} difficulty={3}>
    <p>Do not write an application or <code>Main</code>. Propose only the two public type definitions and short reasons.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Write the C# API for <code>ShippingAddress</code> and <code>Parcel</code>. Choose <code>record</code> or <code>class</code> for each, using constructor, properties, and one transition method as needed.</li>
      <li>For this sequence, give the two Boolean results and the status after each call. Do not add a public setter.</li>
    </ol>
    <Code code={taskCode} lang="csharp" />
    <ol start="3">
      <li>In 2–3 sentences, contrast two independently declared matching address shapes in ordinary TypeScript with independently declared C# <code>ShippingAddress</code> and <code>WarehouseAddress</code> types.</li>
    </ol>
  </ReplyTask>
</SessionPage>
